<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="subsec-sep-minussign" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Separation of Variables: Some Subtle Points</title>

 <p>
    Now we look at two more examples solving separable ODEs. This first example illustrates a subtle point
     when dealing with square roots. See if you can find the mistake in the work below!
 </p>


<exploration xml:id="explore-ivp-sqrt">
  <title>A Subtle Moment in Solving an IVP</title>
  <introduction>
    <p>
      Let's solve the following initial value problem explicitly: <m>x\frac{dx}{dt} = t</m>, <m>x(0) = -2</m>.
    </p>
    <p>
      After separating variables and integrating, we arrive at:
      <me>x^2 = t^2 + C.</me>
    </p>
    <solution>
      <title>Work for separation of variables</title>
      <p>
        First, why is this separable? Notice that <m>x</m> is already on the left with <m>dx</m>, so no dividing by <m>f(x)</m> is necessary — we can separate immediately by writing <m>x\, dx = t\, dt</m>. There are no equilibrium solutions since setting <m>x = C</m> gives <m>0 = t</m>, which can't hold for all <m>t</m>.
      </p>
      <p>
        Separating variables:
        <me>x\, dx = t\, dt.</me>
        Integrating both sides:
        <md>
          <mrow>\int x\, dx \amp= \int t\, dt</mrow>
          <mrow>\frac{1}{2}x^2 \amp= \frac{1}{2}t^2 + C</mrow>
          <mrow>x^2 \amp= t^2 + C.</mrow>
        </md>
      </p>
    </solution>
    <p>
      Now something interesting happens when we solve for <m>x</m> explicitly. Let's take the square root of both sides:
      <me>x(t) = \sqrt{t^2 + C}.</me>
      Applying the initial condition <m>x(0) = -2</m>:
      <me>-2 = \sqrt{0 + C} = \sqrt{C}.</me>
      But the square root of a number is always non-negative — so <m>\sqrt{C} = -2</m> is impossible! We seem to have reached a contradiction. What went wrong?
    </p>
  </introduction>

  <task xml:id="task-find-mistake-sqrt">
    <title>What went wrong?</title>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Identify the error in the working above.
      </p>
    </statement>
    <choices randomize="no">
      <choice>
        <statement><p>We integrated incorrectly. The antiderivative of <m>x</m> is not <m>\frac{1}{2}x^2</m>.</p></statement>
        <feedback><p>Not quite — <m>\int x\, dx = \frac{1}{2}x^2 + C</m> is correct!</p></feedback>
      </choice>
      <choice correct="yes">
        <statement><p>We forgot the <m>\pm</m> when taking the square root.</p></statement>
        <feedback><p>Exactly! When solving <m>x^2 = t^2 + C</m>, we should have written <m>x = \pm\sqrt{t^2 + C}</m>. The negative branch is what allows <m>x(0) = -2</m>.</p></feedback>
      </choice>
      <choice>
        <statement><p>The initial condition <m>x(0) = -2</m> is inconsistent with this ODE, so no solution exists.</p></statement>
        <feedback><p>Not quite — a solution does exist! The issue is earlier in the working.</p></feedback>
      </choice>
    </choices>
  </task>

  <task xml:id="task-correct-solution-sqrt">
    <statement>
      <p>
        Now that you've identified the mistake, see if you can finish solving the problem correctly! Check with the solution below.
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <title>Corrected solution</title>
      <p>
        The fix is to include the <m>\pm</m> when taking the square root:
        <me>x = \pm\sqrt{t^2 + C}.</me>
        Now applying <m>x(0) = -2</m>: since <m>x(0)</m> is negative, we choose the negative branch:
        <me>-2 = -\sqrt{C} \implies \sqrt{C} = 2 \implies C = 4.</me>
        So the specific solution is:
        <me>x(t) = -\sqrt{t^2 + 4}.</me>
      </p>
    </solution>
  </task>

</exploration>

<p>
  So far, when solving a separable ODE we have always ended by solving explicitly for the dependent 
  variable, arriving at something like <m>y = Ce^{2x}</m> or <m>x = -\sqrt{t^2 + 4}</m>. But sometimes it is difficult or 
  even impossible to isolate the dependent variable, and that's okay! 
  An equation relating <m>y</m> and <m>x</m> that implicitly defines <m>y</m> as a function of <m>x</m>,
   without explicitly writing <m>y = \ldots</m>, is called an <term>implicit solution</term>. 
   For example, <m>y^2 + x^2 = C</m> could be an implicit solution to an ODE even though we haven't written <m>y</m> by itself. In these cases,
    we simply stop once we have a clean implicit relation and call that the general solution.
</p>

<example xml:id="ex-implicit-solution">
  <title>Finding a General Implicit Solution</title>
  <introduction>
  <p>
    Find a general implicit solution to <m>v'(t) = \frac{1}{v} - \frac{t^2}{v}</m>.
    Before diving in, see if you can figure out whether there are any equilibrium solutions!
  </p>
</introduction>
  <task xml:id="task-separate-implicit">
    <title>Separating the variables</title>
    <statement>
      <p>
         We are trying to solve <m>v'(t) = \frac{1}{v} - \frac{t^2}{v}</m>.
        Which of the following correctly separates the variables?
      </p>
    </statement>
    <choices randomize="yes">
      <choice correct="yes">
        <statement>
          <p><m>\displaystyle\int v\, dv = \int (1 - t^2)\, dt</m></p>
        </statement>
        <feedback>
          <p>Correct! Multiplying both sides by <m>v</m> gives <m>v\frac{dv}{dt} = 1 - t^2</m>, and then separating gives <m>v\, dv = (1-t^2)\, dt</m>.</p>
        </feedback>
      </choice>
      <choice>
        <statement>
          <p><m>\displaystyle\int \frac{1}{v}\, dv = \int (1 - t^2)\, dt</m></p>
        </statement>
        <feedback>
          <p>Not quite — check your separation step. You need to multiply both sides by <m>v</m> first, not divide.</p>
        </feedback>
      </choice>
      <choice>
        <statement>
          <p><m>\displaystyle\int v\, dv = \int \left(-\frac{t^2}{v}\right) dt</m></p>
        </statement>
        <feedback>
          <p>Not quite — the right-hand side still contains <m>v</m>, which means the variables are not fully separated!</p>
        </feedback>
      </choice>
      <choice>
        <statement>
          <p>This ODE is not separable.</p>
        </statement>
        <feedback>
          <p>It is separable! Try rewriting the right-hand side by factoring out <m>\frac{1}{v}</m>: <m>v' = \frac{1-t^2}{v}</m>. Now can you see how to separate?</p>
        </feedback>
      </choice>
    </choices>
    <solution>
      <title>How to separate the variables</title>
      <p>
        First notice <m>v' </m> is the same thing as <m>\frac{dv}{dt} </m>, and we can rewrite the right-hand side by combining the fractions:
        <me>\frac{dv}{dt} = \frac{1}{v} - \frac{t^2}{v} = \frac{1 - t^2}{v}.</me>
        Now multiply both sides by <m>v</m>:
        <me>v \cdot \frac{dv}{dt} = 1 - t^2 \implies v\, dv = (1 - t^2)\, dt.</me>
        Integrating both sides:
        <me>\int v\, dv = \int (1 - t^2)\, dt.</me>
      </p>
    </solution>
  </task>

  <task xml:id="task-implicit-integrate">
    <title>Integrating and writing the implicit solution</title>
    <statement>
      <p>
        After integrating both sides, we arrive at:
        <me>\frac{1}{2}v^2 = t - \frac{1}{3}t^3 + C.</me>
        This is the general implicit solution. See the dropdown for all the details.
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <title>Full working</title>
      <p>
  <alert>Equilibrium solutions:</alert> None.
</p>
<solution>
  <title>Why are there no equilibrium solutions?</title>
  <p>
    Rewriting the ODE as <m>\frac{dv}{dt} = \frac{1}{v}(1 - t^2)</m>, we have
    <m>f(v) = \frac{1}{v}</m>. Setting <m>f(v) = 0</m> gives <m>\frac{1}{v} = 0</m>,
    which has no solution. So there are no equilibrium solutions.
  </p>
</solution>
      <p>
        <alert>Separating and integrating:</alert>
        <md>
          <mrow>v\, dv \amp= (1 - t^2)\, dt</mrow>
          <mrow>\int v\, dv \amp= \int (1 - t^2)\, dt</mrow>
          <mrow>\frac{1}{2}v^2 \amp= t - \frac{1}{3}t^3 + C.</mrow>
        </md>
        Since solving explicitly for <m>v</m> would require taking a square root (introducing a <m>\pm</m>) and the problem only asks for an implicit solution, we stop here. The general implicit solution is:
        <me>\frac{1}{2}v^2 = t - \frac{1}{3}t^3 + C.</me>
      </p>
    </solution>
  </task>

</example>

